ðŸ”¹ What Are Conditional Statements?

Conditional statements allow your program to make decisions and execute code only if certain conditions are true.

Python uses:

if â†’ checks a condition

elif â†’ checks another condition if previous if failed

else â†’ executes if all conditions are false

1ï¸âƒ£ Basic Syntax
x = 10

if x > 0:
    print("Positive")
elif x == 0:
    print("Zero")
else:
    print("Negative")
print('All done')


Output:

Positive
All done


Donâ€™t forget:

Colon : is mandatory after if, elif, and else.

Indentation is mandatory (usually 4 spaces).

2ï¸âƒ£ Smart Things to Know
a) Boolean Expressions

Conditions must evaluate to True or False.

Can use comparison operators:
==, !=, >, <, >=, <=

Can use logical operators: and, or, not

age = 20
if age > 18 and age < 30:
    print("Young adult")

b) Python allows short forms / one-liners
x = 5
print("Even") if x % 2 == 0 else print("Odd")

c) Multiple conditions

Use nested if statements carefully.

x = 10
if x > 0:
    if x % 2 == 0:
        print("Positive even")


Or use elif chains for clarity.

3ï¸âƒ£ Comparison & Identity

== â†’ checks value equality

is â†’ checks if both variables point to the same object

Smart to know difference:

a = [1,2]
b = [1,2]
print(a == b)  # True (same value)
print(a is b)  # False (different objects)

4ï¸âƒ£ Doâ€™s and Donâ€™ts
âœ… Doâ€™s

Always use meaningful conditions.

Use elif instead of multiple if where only one condition should execute.

Keep conditions readable; break complex ones into variables if needed.

Test edge cases (like 0, negative numbers, empty lists).

âŒ Donâ€™ts

Donâ€™t forget colons : after if, elif, else.

Donâ€™t mix tabs and spaces â€” Python will throw IndentationError.

Donâ€™t write if x = 5 â†’ = is assignment, use ==.

Avoid too many nested ifs â†’ reduces readability.

5ï¸âƒ£ Advanced / Smart Things

Truthy and Falsy values

Python treats some values as False in conditions:
0, 0.0, "", None, [], {}, set(), False

0 (int)

0.0 (float)

"" (empty string)

[] (empty list)

{} (empty dict)

set() (empty set)

None

False

Everything else is True.

eg1: Because instead of writing long conditions like:

if len(my_list) > 0:
    print("List not empty")


You can just write:

if my_list:
    print("List not empty")


Python automatically checks truthiness. âœ”ï¸

my_list = []
if my_list:
    print("Not empty")
else:
    print("Empty")  # âœ… prints Empty


Ternary operator (one-line if-else)

status = "Adult" if age >= 18 else "Minor"


Combine multiple conditions smartly

score = 85
if 80 <= score <= 100:
    print("A grade")


This avoids writing score >= 80 and score <= 100.

Check membership

Use in / not in to simplify checks:

fruit = "apple"
if fruit in ["apple", "banana", "mango"]:
    print("Available")

6ï¸âƒ£ Donâ€™t Forget Quick Checklist

âœ… Colons : after if, elif, else

âœ… Proper indentation (4 spaces)

âœ… Comparison vs assignment (== vs =)

âœ… Use elif instead of multiple if for exclusive conditions

âœ… Test edge/falsy values

âœ… Boolean operators (and, or, not)

âœ… Membership (in, not in)

âœ… Ternary operator for one-liners

ðŸ”‘ Mnemonic / Memory Trick

â€œIf Else Elif Decide True / False Clearlyâ€

If â†’ check first condition

Else â†’ default/fallback

Elif â†’ extra conditions

Decide â†’ execute only if True

True/False â†’ boolean logic

Clearly â†’ keep code readable